Read (and filter) county features into an sf dataframe and plot

In this exercise, we will be exploring stream gage height data in Nebraska corresponding to floods occurring there in 2019. First, we will import from the US Counties shapefile weve used in lab lessons, filtering it this time for just Nebraska counties. Nebraskas state FIPS code is 31 (as North Carolinas was 37).

  1. Read the cb_2018_us_county_20m.shp shapefile into an sf dataframe, filtering records for Nebraska counties (State FIPS = 31)
  2. Reveal the datasets coordinate reference system
  3. Plot the records as a map (using mapview or ggplot)
#3. Read in Counties shapefile into an sf dataframe, filtering for just NE counties
counties = st_read(here("Data","Spatial","cb_2018_us_county_20m.shp")) %>% 
  filter(STATEFP == "31")

#5. Plot the data
mapview(counties)
  1. What is the EPSG code of the Counties dataset? Is this a geographic or a projected coordinate reference system? (Om other words, does this CRS use angular or planar coordinate units?) To what datum is this CRS associated? (Tip: look for the EPSG code on https://epsg.io)

ANSWER: the EPSG code for the counties dataset can typically be found as EPSG 4269, representing the North American Datum 1983 (NAD83). This is a geographic coordinate reference system, meaning it uses degrees to define positions on the Earths surface rather than planar units like meters or feet. This datum and CRS are common for US based spatial datasets.

Convert the dataframe to a spatial features (sf) dataframe

  1. Convert the dataframe to an sf dataframe. * Note: These data use the same coordinate reference system as the counties dataset

  2. Display the structure of the resulting sf dataframe

#10. Convert to an sf object
nwis_sf = st_as_sf(nwis, coords = c("dec_long_va", "dec_lat_va"),
                   crs = st_crs(counties))

#11. Display the structure
str(nwis_sf)

  1. What new field(s) appear in the sf dataframe created? What field(s), if any, disappeared?

ANSWER: in the conversion to an sf dataframe, a new field called geometry appears, which stores the longitude and latitude coordinates for each record. The original fields dec_lat_va and dec_long_va no longer appear as separate columns, as they are now incorporated into the geometry field.

Map the pattern of gage height data

Now we can examine where the flooding appears most acute by visualizing gage heights spatially. 19. Plot the gage sites on top of counties (using mapview, ggplot, or leaflet) * Show the magnitude of gage height by color, shape, other visualization technique.

#Map the points, sized by gage height

SPATIAL ANALYSIS

Up next we will do some spatial analysis with our data. To prepare for this, we should transform our data into a projected coordinate system. Well choose UTM Zone 14N (EPGS = 32614).

Transform the counties and gage site datasets to UTM Zone 14N

  1. Transform the counties and gage sf datasets to UTM Zone 14N (EPGS = 32614).
  2. Using mapview or ggplot, plot the data so that each can be seen as different colors
#20 Transform the counties and gage location datasets to UTM Zone 14
counties_utm = st_transform(counties, crs = 32614)
nwis_flow_utm = st_transform(nwis_flow, crs = 32614)

#21 Plot the data
mapview(counties_utm) +
  mapview(nwis_flow_utm, zcol = "gage_ht", cex = "gage_ht",
          col.regions = list('purple','darkblue'))
## Warning: Found less unique colors (2) than unique zcol values (124)! 
## Interpolating color vector to match number of zcol values.

Select the gages falling within a given county

Now lets zoom into a particular county and examine the gages located there. 22. Select Lancaster county from your projected county sf dataframe 23. Select the gage sites falling within that county to a new spatial dataframe 24. Select the gage sites within 15km of the county to a new spatial dataframe 25. Create a plot showing (each symbolized distinctly): * all Nebraska counties, * the selected county, * the gage sites in that county, * and the gage sites within 15 km of the county

#22 Select the county
lancaster = counties_utm %>% 
  filter(NAME == "Lancaster")

#23 Spatially select gages within the selected county
gages_in_lancaster = nwis_flow_utm %>%
  st_intersection(lancaster)
## Warning: attribute variables are assumed to be spatially constant throughout
## all geometries
#24 Spatially select gages within 15 k of the selected county
buffer_15km = st_buffer(lancaster, dist = 15000)
buffer_ring = st_difference(buffer_15km, lancaster)
## Warning: attribute variables are assumed to be spatially constant throughout
## all geometries
gages_in_ring = nwis_flow_utm %>%
  st_intersection(buffer_ring)
## Warning: attribute variables are assumed to be spatially constant throughout
## all geometries
#25 Plot
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = counties_utm, fill = "cadetblue1", color = "cadetblue4") +
  geom_sf(data = lancaster, fill = "paleturquoise3", color = "paleturquoise3") +
  geom_sf(data = gages_in_lancaster, fill = "palevioletred1",
          color = "palevioletred1", size = 2, shape = 15) +
  geom_sf(data = gages_in_ring, fill = "rosybrown1", color = "rosybrown1",
          size = 2, shape = 16) +
  labs(title = "Gage Sites in and near Lancaster County") +
  theme_minimal()
